{
  "text": "To assess the integrity of the ileum tissues collected at 21 dpc, a range of intestinal cell lineage markers was evaluated and quantified. In particular, molecular markers that identify secretion (PAS signal and Mucin2, MUC2), absorption and homeostasis (Intestinal alkaline phosphatase, IAP), apoptosis (Cleaved-caspase3, CASP3) and immune cell distribution (Calprotectin, CP) were monitored (Figs. 5 and 6) [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . In the vaccinated group (n = 23) the level of PAS, MUC2 as well as IAP was significantly higher than controls (n = 25; p < .01, p < .01, p < .001, respectively). IAP expression in vaccinated pigs was similar to the level found in the sentinels (n = 5; p > .05). Expression of apoptotic marker CASP3 was significantly up-regulated in controls (p < .05) pigs compared to the sentinels. CP, a marker associated with neutrophil infiltration, was expressed at a higher level compared to the sentinels, in both controls (p > .05) and vaccinates (p < .05).",
  "correct_citation": {
